<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="371" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,151,617]" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,517,542]" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished by the short aedeagal shaft with ventrally curved apical appendages and short 
<number box="[399,413,557,581]" pageId="10" pageNumber="371" value="2.0">2</number>
nd abdominal apodemes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1362,592,617]" pageId="10" pageNumber="371" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,151,617]" box="[199,1362,592,617]" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,592,617]" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName box="[580,703,592,616]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macrosteles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="371" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harperatus">
<emphasis box="[580,703,592,616]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="371">harperatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” refers to the hooklike apical appendages of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
